      <article id="comment-4547" class="comment article">
        <h3><a href="http://mediacommons.futureofthebook.org/imr/2013/08/06/data-collection-television-and-twitter#comment-4547" class="active">the muscle milk effect</a></h3>
        <div class="vcard"><a href="http://mediacommons.futureofthebook.org/imr/users/matthew-stoddard" title="View user profile." rel="contact" class="url"><img src="http://mediacommons.futureofthebook.org/imr/files/pictures/picture-6364.jpg" alt="Matthew Stoddard&#039;s picture" title="Matthew Stoddard&#039;s picture" class="photo"></a> by <a href="http://mediacommons.futureofthebook.org/imr/users/matthew-stoddard" title="View Matthew Stoddard&#039;s profile" class="realname">Matthew Stoddard</a> <span class="org">University of Minnesota</span></div>
        <time datetime="2013-08-09T08:32+00:00">August 09, 2013 – 08:32</time>
        <p>Michael, I think this ambiguity around targeting that you point to (and which Ethan indicates as well) is extremely interesting. It seems to push our relation to ads and our relation to our selves vis-a-vis those ads towards a kind of existential vertigo (I don&#8217;t need muscle milk, or do I?), and layers of meta commentary. Maybe this twisting self referencing and self questioning is the logical extension of the play of irony in &#8216;modern&#8217; advertising (Volkwagen&#8217;s famous &#8220;lemon&#8221; ad)&#8230; </p>
